President Biden introduced Judge Ketanji Jackson as his nominee for the United States Supreme Court. He praised her qualifications, character, and integrity, emphasizing the importance of a diverse and reflective Court. Judge Jackson, if confirmed, would fill the seat of retiring Justice Stephen Breyer. She has a background as a federal public defender, a trial court judge, and a judge on the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia. She has been confirmed by the Senate three times before and is highly respected for her legal expertise and fairness. In her remarks, Judge Jackson expressed her gratitude for the nomination and discussed her family, mentors, and commitment to equal justice under the law. She also mentioned that she shares a birthday with the first Black woman federal judge, Judge Constance Baker Motley, whom she considers an inspiration.